# Nullish coalescing

Use **`??`** (nullish coalescing) instead of **`||`** when providing a fallback for `null` or `undefined`.

- `??` only falls back when the left side is `null` or `undefined`.
- `||` also treats `0`, `''`, and `false` as falsy and replaces them, which is often unintended.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD – replaces 0, '', false
const count = value || 10;
const name = user.name || 'Anonymous';

// ✅ GOOD – only replaces null/undefined
const count = value ?? 10;
const name = user.name ?? 'Anonymous';
```

Use `||` only when you intentionally want to treat all falsy values the same (e.g. empty string → default).
